I agree with the points made in the above postings.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="10" relname="span"> However there are a few firms who actually make an effort for the novice user.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="justify"> I work as a Quality assurance engineer responsible to make sure that an application works according to application requirements and that an application can be used by a novice application user.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="9" relname="span"> In general I think the term &quot;novice&quot; is loosely used as a Novice application user need not be a Novice computer user.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> The nature of an application should determine the level of expertise required by the end user.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="8" relname="span"> 
Many new age firms design applications that are sent thru a process of end user testing conducted by a target audience of users who define a part of the actual application users.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration"> This helps to define the application for the application users who are both experts and novice in the use of the application. 
</segment>
